From 27 BCE until 180 CE, the Roman Empire enjoyed relative peace and stability during the Pax Romana. The mighty Roman military backed the Pax Romana. The Roman army controlled the empire's enormous domains and suppressed rebellions and invasions, ensuring peace and stability. The Pax Romana was also supported by the Roman judicial system, which upheld justice and order. Religious tolerance by the Roman government helped unite the empire's varied populace. 